04453nam a22007095i 9780813541020DE-B159720220524034747.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220524t20062006nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97808135410207 a10.36019/97808135410202doi  a(DE-B1597)526243  a(OCoLC)1058894081  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 4aHV752.L7 7aHIS0000002bisacsh04a305.23/086/940942109034a305.230869409421090341 aMurdoch, Lydia, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aImagined Orphans :bPoor Families, Child Welfare, and Contested Citizenship in London /cLydia Murdoch. 1aNew Brunswick, NJ : bRutgers University Press, c[2006] 4c©2006  a1 online resource (288 p.) :b24 b&w illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aRutgers Series in Childhood Studies0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWith his dirty, tattered clothes and hollowed-out face, Oliver Twist is the enduring symbol of the young indigent spilling out of orphanages and haunting the streets of late-nineteenth-century London. Although poor children were often portrayed as real-life Oliver Twists—either orphaned or abandoned by unworthy parents—they in fact frequently maintained contact and were eventually reunited with their families. In Imagined Orphans, Lydia Murdoch focuses on this discrepancy between the representation and the reality of children’s experiences within welfare institutions—a discrepancy that she argues stems from conflicts over middle- and working-class notions of citizenship that arose in the 1870s and persisted until the First World War. Reformers’ efforts to depict poor children as either orphaned or endangered by abusive or “no-good” parents fed upon the poor’s increasing exclusion from the Victorian social body. Reformers used the public’s growing distrust and pitiless attitude toward poor adults to increase charity and state aid to the children. With a critical eye to social issues of the period, Murdoch urges readers to reconsider the complex situations of families living in poverty. While reformers’ motivations seem well intentioned, she shows how their methods solidified the public’s antipoor sentiment and justified a minimalist welfare state that engendered a cycle of poverty. As they worked to fashion model citizens, reformers’ efforts to protect and care for children took on an increasingly imperial cast that would continue into the twentieth century.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Mai 2022) 0aChild welfarezEnglandzLondonxHistoryy19th century. 0aChild welfarezEnglandzLondonxHistoryy20th century. 0aPoor childrenxInstitutional carezEnglandzLondonxHistoryy19th century. 0aPoor childrenxInstitutional carezEnglandzLondonxHistoryy20th century. 0aPoor familieszEnglandzLondonxHistoryy19th century. 0aPoor familieszEnglandzLondonxHistoryy20th century. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertRutgers University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311068861040uhttps://doi.org/10.36019/978081354102040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780813541020423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780813541020/original  a978-3-11-068861-0  Rutgers University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK